      {
        "paragraph_index": 2,
        "text": "### Chemistry Insights\n\n1. **Fe³⁺ wins universally.** The preference for Fe³⁺ holds across all ligand classes — from simple inorganic anions to large multidentate chelators. This reflects Fe³⁺'s higher charge (+3 vs +2) and smaller ionic radius, making it a harder and stronger Lewis acid that forms shorter, more electrostatic bonds with donor atoms.\n\n2. **Hard O-donor ligands show the largest preference for Fe³⁺.** Catecholates, hydroxamates, phenolates, and carboxylates all show Δlog β > 7 log units. This is the chemical basis for biological iron sequestration — siderophores like desferrioxamine B evolved to exploit this enormous thermodynamic preference (Δlog β ≈ +20.6), achieving essentially irreversible Fe³⁺ capture under physiological conditions.\n\n3. **Soft/π-donor ligands narrow the gap considerably.** 1,10-Phenanthroline (Δ = +0.7) and 2,2′-bipyridine (Δ = +1.6) show much smaller differences because Fe²⁺ is a better π-back-donor to these N-heterocyclic ligands. In redox-active systems, this near-parity is exploited: the Fe²⁺/Fe³⁺ couple can be tuned by ligand choice, and tris(bipy)Fe²⁺ is kinetically very stable even though Fe³⁺ is still thermodynamically slightly ahead.\n\n**Source:** NIST SRD-46 (Critically Selected Stability Constants of Metal Complexes Database)",
        "claims": [
          {
            "start": 0,
            "end": 22,
            "text": "### Chemistry Insights",
            "claim_type": "filler",
            "metadata": {
              "classifier_strategy_version": "react-v7-schema-salvage-markdown-anchor",
              "classifier_round": 0,
              "classifier_stage": "initial"
            }
          },
          {
            "start": 27,
            "end": 53,
